A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year itself.
Maybe
The mobile market in Chechnya is relatively advanced, our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force the classic operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The CTU (the Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of a SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, has also confirmed it.
As a result, following the European Commission's last steps in the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may arise - the SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, since we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that is well over 100 per cent.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Czech Telecommunications Office Board (CTU), who said several times that there was no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, complained to the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with his own network has apparently no more chance (at present he would find only difficult frequencies).
But there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a significant decrease in prices, to which the traditional operators also had to respond.
However, even before the entry of trouble parties such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, voices similar to those heard today at home were being heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was room for such operators and that they could have real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch of the virtual Mobilking operator in Poland.
In just six months, this operator has managed to win over 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator of the country.
Let us add that behind the Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which has among other things the U:fon in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they really need much less customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the costs of construction, operation and entry of the mobile, relatively high network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators profile as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers, in Great Britain, at least two times less expensive SMS than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, missing on an unusual target group can also be a good time for advertising.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and they can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, exploiting this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be possible to walk with us too.
Miroslav Čepýk, Vodafone's spokesperson, in doubt: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmentary approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
As much as it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In Chechnya, no chance, the mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project successfully, but negotiations in Chechnya are not very provocative.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area," says Jana Studnikkova, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do their best to make a potential competitor appear.
The GTS Novera Group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Teleika in the area of business customers, does not hide, for quite a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We have a lot to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile.
And the sooner it'll be the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have succeeded in moving forward in the negotiations," said the spokesperson of the Pavel Kaidl group.
So the future may be promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we might be able to welcome the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for the moment, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At this point, we do not believe that there is a place on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is compared to other very specific ones.
For the time being, no matter provided with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," Vlastimil Sršený of the Press Department of Phoneika O2, mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with the O2: "We have not recorded for the moment a viable and bilaterally beneficial project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time frame, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone, on the other hand, directs its attention to the compliance of requests to obtain its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepiký said in this regard: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we believe to be the most important contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile Internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a lower price and thus a lower profit.
So what's good about making it easier for such a competitor?
As far as their interests are concerned, operators know how to understand themselves as they do. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U.S. background also testifies to this.
The biggest apparent pressure on CTU, during the creation of the U-Fon, was the one exercised by the T-Mobile company.
They testify to the information available to the public from the CTU website.
Now, today, the U:Fon is ready to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this regard: "The competition on the mobile market has also been recently amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
In view of the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player will submit it, and especially its services, to high requirements."
However, given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies appears to be disappointing.
However, this is not only the attitude of the CTU, which, contrary to Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator on the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached for the time being, because the offer of potential stakeholders did not give sufficient priority to classical operators," Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS said in response to our question.
A statement thus made would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
However, on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one benefits from its position on the market, such a statement is more than a waste.
The more Kristian Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their market entry has contributed to a decline in mobile phone service prices."
However, pressure in the sense of an honest functioning of the market and a price reduction is apparently not part of the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is really shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, resulting from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, is of course a matter.
Similarly, a price of strictly identical essence to all service stations is probably due to the accident and hard fighting of competition.
"The office has not, in this regard, recorded signs of anti-competitive behaviour, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators have a dominant position, none of them therefore have an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably even lacking to the telecommunication regulator," said Chaloupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by CTU, according to which telecommunications is, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some law experts suggest a different view of things: in order for a virtual operator to be able, it is necessary to obtain, at each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are manifestly performing in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in the negotiations with all operators.
Reducing responsibility for CTU is a fairly common turn in communications, whereby the CTU washes the hands of the case.
We have already met this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, there has been no success in the modernization of the telecommunications Act, which has recently been adopted, an extension of CTU's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
This is something that the representatives of ÚOHS need to know very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can go
That says, the operation of a kind of virtual pseudo operators, several in the Czech mobile networks, remains undetected.
These are companies publishing their own price list of mobile telephone services, but the latter are only partially public.
In most cases, it is a matter of firm dealing with multi-level marketing.
This is how specific mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these companies are generally only available to the electorate.
The magic tour consists of the fact that the company is performing before the operator is a classic company client, which controls a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it receives special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a return.
"If what you say was happening, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions that we would consider and that could result in a ceasefire with the company in question," answered our question about this problem, Martina Kemrová.
However, it is unlikely that an echo of such an activity has not been reached to the managers of the mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, thousands of customers may be involved.
However, no operator shall object to such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them unresolved benefits, and, at the same time, in opposition to true virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepýk indicates the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, they are obliged to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered on their behalf, so they cannot have it fully available as regular customers of mobile operators."
However, this is precisely what should be strange in the CTU.
In addition, there is another question in the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that ÚOHS has relatively wide powers to open up such an activity, and if it does not wish to be content with the operator's explanations, which claims to have no idea what would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer the most expensive country
As we have mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant decline in the price of services.
In almost all countries where virtual operators appeared, however, classical operators were increasingly, less and less, trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that in developed countries, regulatory agencies, which did not defend the interests of mobile operators, but those of their clients, have intervened.
Both through formal measures and through informal pressure, they ended up getting the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are dealing with this issue in the way of a hot potato that is depleted by passing it to a close target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in their skills is more than beneficial in these cases.
But don't throw the trigger after the cognition.
If the information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at our home, the Czech mobile market may be moving back.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS can hardly remain impeccable in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And maybe we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech Hymne has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech National Hymne.
On Sunday, on the day of the Czech Nationality, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the National Hymne Where is my home? (Where is my home?).
Hymne was re-registered by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with heart and an instrumental version.
The song is provided by Katerín Kniežinková et Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the Hymne arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rzhlas (Czech public radio), he chose to interpret the solo versions of the singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both singers, as well as the heart, had a good sentence, so that we could understand the words, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech National Hymne will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde mův můj můj held for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovča (Kermesse des saviers), the original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Til, accompanied by the music by František Škroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously adapted it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple naturally became an integral part of the National Hymne.
It will remain one of the seven national symbols even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic.
