The Sutes were demanding a referendum in the United States
The Germans of the South asked in 1945 for Shumava to be integrated into the United States.
This comes from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vedecká knikhna (The Scientific Library of the South Bohème).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the US patronage.
In 1945, certain groups of Germans in the South addressed the President of the United States with such a wish.
This comes from, among other things, a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vedecká knikhna.
From the Germans of Český Krumlov in the letter, the US President does not allow "shuavská zupa" (a region of forests south of Bohème) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have well understood the situation, and we want to be sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come into the German territory not in oppressors and enemies, but in liberators," is written in the letter "People to whom the fate of the Shumava is at heart."
Given that the relationship with Czechoslovakia is not allegedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - that of brutality, indifference, misunderstanding, oppression and bondage, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take in his hands the protection of the Shumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would give this territory to a foreign state, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which has not contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the four million inhabitants," the letter says.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire to avenge the "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans in Shumava, he would only have to organize a referendum in the region, according to the authors, to establish whether his people wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the United States patronage.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of the history of post-war, appear to be somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Germans of the Southers of the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least consider that the issue of their expulsion from the republic was going to take place, very few of them had had such an opportunity.
Some expected that the United States and Britain would obtain a certain type of autonomy for the South.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirmed it.
