As soon as we turn to other species and approach the questions of the senses or in general of consciousness, we will enter difficultly practical fields because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it causes death, flees, or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, so some scientists deduct a comparable subjective life from it.
I don't believe it, though.
Two aspects of the brain structure make the transformation of our subjective life to that of the difficult animals.
One aspect is that the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the frontal lateral cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in management and execution functions).
This vast region is much more developed in human beings than in other primates and appears to be completely absent in other beings.
