In February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer be repeated.
While Judge Krever was delaying his report, some provinces had then set up a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to provide all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, only 38 per cent of the people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Dr. Decary recalled.
The situation was discouraging.
With efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground during the years that followed, we regained the public confidence," she said before she said she was proud that in early 2008, almost 94% of the people of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Decary, however, maintains that "trust is something extremely fragile."
On 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of the disease of the mad cow, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were seen in Europe.
