But a few years ago, it was no doubt shown that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle applied had meaning."
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV testing technique appeared on the market: nuclear acid (TAN) tests that directly detect in donor blood the presence of the virus itself, not the anti-virus antibodies, on which the tests were used until then.
The TANs have allowed the period of mutagenicity, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our technicians, explains the specialist.
This period was reduced to less than one week.
This has significantly reduced the risk of some donors being infected without knowledge and cannot be detected.
These improvements have led to a significant reduction in the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, a person of 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
