Over-the-counter psychology: why do we spend more money?
In the course of sales, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have been able to update the neurological and economic bases of this well-known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced from this type of competition, such as sales to eBay auctions, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
These research has attempted to develop a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" with the help of sales to experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lot, while the other group participated in a sale to the gaming auctions, while with the help of a functional magnetic resonance process (IRMf), researchers analyzed the active brain areas of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants were able to earn money, but during the sale of the auctions, an essential element of which is the overload of a third, the whole under the brain trunk, called striatum, was moving intensely during the loss of the part.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the "auto-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to researchers, the rise of prices is explained by the leak in front of the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial monitoring analyses.
In these cases, three groups faced a partner, under different circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus they did so.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they were winning the party, then they would receive 15 additional dollars, in reward.
While the third group received these $15 before the auctions, the members of the group also lost that money, if they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed at one on victory, while at the other on failure.
By thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the team of players "against failure" were available at higher positions than those carried out by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any already existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them did not explain the phenomena found in sales to auctions, but by the pleasure of winning and the parade at risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging have helped to eliminate the contradiction between the two theories by now starting on a third explanation." - Andrew Schutter, professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences at the University of New York, observed.
Hepatitis: when do we have to consult a doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
There are hundreds of miles of hepatitis virus patients in Hungary, but only seven miles of treatment follow. This is because often the patients do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. The inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, are mainly spread in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g., food or contaminated water), hepatitis B, C, D and other blood viruses and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, generally accompanied by a bad general condition, weakness, stomach and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white eye a visible yellowish, the cells become clearer and the urine takes a more dark color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year a million people die of the most serious form of this pathology, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one patient in ten receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it may lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know how to get the virus because the pathogen destroys the liver cells in a subtle way. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average of a population of three groups: individuals who had undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, patients with chronic hepatitis C in the world are estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is recommended that you consult your doctor to treat symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
On 30 September, the World Day of Hepatitis was first organized by the agencies representing the sick of the four corners of the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of chronic liver caused by viruses, to the causes of its development and to the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
