The Smart Car Imitates the Flights of the Bourdon
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle if it was not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
For example, the one with the bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the baroning bees gave the strategic idea of departure to Nissan engineers to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacles detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot, a bio-inspired auto-robotized system, type BR23C, which he equipped with bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
In its flights, each bee is its own area, oval-shaped, which, in reality, looks much like our safe-guarded cocoon - explained, at the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the Department of Research and Development and the technology relations of the brand.
The bee facet eye plays a key role, as it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the function of the face-to-face eye, engineers have addressed the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the microprocessor, which transforms it into an escape handle immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from an angle enough to avoid collision.
In contrast to any existing system at present, this prevention exercise takes place in an instinctive manner.
"If not, the mini robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotized car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and the most internal layer of the protection envelope, a layer where the collision is now considered inevitable.
All this process must reflect what the bee does to avoid the other bee.
The process must take place in an eyelid.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combined bees that have the bees to avoid the other bees, in our case, only the rotating movement, acceleration and slowing as manoeuvres at the disposal of the mini robot
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and whose energy concentration is larger, making their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is primary, not data processing, and even less storage capacity.
This mechanism must treat only a few signals coming in a second, and respond to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilo-octets of continuous memory.
We don't need memory of a giga-octets capacity, or even mega-octets.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology used for instant avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will enter the cars manufactured in the next ten years.
Another application could be its integration into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on its way.
