Industrial prices continued to increase
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 per cent compared to the month of August 2007 - reported by the Central Office of Statistics of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to those of one year ago, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of domestic and export fluctuations, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to those of the previous month, and 3.2 per cent compared to those of the previous year.
The domestic industrial sales prices increased only to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry were only slightly increased by 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first production of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then production of footwear with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials have resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in a decline in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), and a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry have recorded an increase of 0.2 per cent and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent an important weight in national industrial operation, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the gas price introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, these are the prices of the oil processing sector that have experienced the most significant increase (32.4%).
In the manufacture of metallurgical products, an increase in prices of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the important area of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Prices decreased in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the production of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the whole processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent of the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to sector allocations, in August, these are the investment profit-initiating sectors that have shown the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials production sectors for subsequent transformation did not have any change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the most significant increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for subsequent transformation (16.8 per cent).
In the production sectors of consumer goods, inflation has been measured by 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-initiating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent has been observed.
The export sales prices of the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they decreased by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national payment average decreased by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent compared to the euro and 15.9 per cent compared to the dollar.
