Mp3 player points the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening from full volume music for a extended period using portable music devices such as Mp3 readers may cause permanent injury to the hearing.
This is what the European Commission, which, in a communiqué distributed in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks of the EU (Csseri), published today.
"of this scientific report - read us in the note - it turns out that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable musical devices, for more than an hour per day and per week, are at risk of permanent loss of hearing ability."
"I am concerned that a large number of young people who often use portable musical devices and mobile phones in full volume can inadvertently damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"Scientific data indicate that the person responsible continues to pose a clear risk and we must respond quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
In addition, we need to review existing systems of control in view of the scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise generated by them.
"Scientific-concluding the Executive U-Confirms that there are good reasons to worry, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of musical devices to 100Db, but concerns about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these data using solutions such as the reduction of levels and the duration of noise exposure.
The Scientific Committee notes that portable music users, who listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, exceed the current limits for maximum noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music under such conditions for extended periods are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
